<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-153-850  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 153 850.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>InfoWorld  April 3 1989 v11 n14 p40(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Zenith pursues protested Air Force contract.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Mace, Scott.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Six computer vendors are bidding for the US Air Force's five-yearcontract for desktop computers.andP;  The Desktop III request for bidscalls for 250,000 microcomputers worth millions of dollars.andO;Zenith Data Systems was awarded the last two contracts, the mostrecent of which expired in Feb 1989.andP;  Two classes of desktopcomputers are specified: basic personal workstations, and advancedworkstations capable of running multitasking applications, networkserver software, and stand-alone software.andP;  The processor must becapable of running DOS applications.andP;  International TechnologyCorp (ITC) filed a protest alleging the bid 'effectively limitscompetition to manufacturers or those large system integratorswith close ties to manufacturers.' ITC requests the contract bebroken into pieces.andP;  The GSA Board of Contract Appeals suspendedthe procurement and scheduled a hearing for Apr 17, 1989.andP;  DefenseDepartment agencies are currently buying over 6,000 PCs per monththrough the GSA's group pricing contract.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Air ForceContractsMicrocomputersUnited States. Department of DefenseRequest for ProposalsCompetitive Bidding.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   Competing for Air Force desktops. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>